review: I wasn’t inclined to pick up this book. Too much hype and the cover didn’t catch my attention. But a friend picked it for book club and so I began. I’I wasn’t inclined to pick up this book. Too much hype and the cover didn’t catch my attention. But a friend picked it for book club and so I began. I’m so glad that I did. This book is right up my alley. I loved the Hollywood aspect to it. Even though they are all fictional, it had that gossip quality to it with the story being told and the real one behind the curtain. Evelyn Hugo was a complex character and the telling of her story with hindsight allowed the reader to know all the reasoning behind her choices. In the end, it’s a love story that wasn’t expected from a book that caught me off guard. I really liked it....more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This book brought up so many ethical questions. How do you respect family choice, culture and religion while still questioning and advocating for moreThis book brought up so many ethical questions. How do you respect family choice, culture and religion while still questioning and advocating for more for an individual? Arlo is a DeafBlind man in his twenties who has been sheltered and lied to by the people that are supposed to love him, protect him and teach him. When he finally meets Cyril, an interpreter, who plants the seeds for Arlo to ask questions, his world opens up.This book tells so much about the experience of a DeafBlind individual but does it through storytelling. The reader learns so much through the dialogue of characters with each other. The narrative never pulls the reader out to teach them. Blair Fell, weaves all the nuances of accessibility and advocacy into Arlo’s story. As someone who is familiar with the Deaf community, I loved this coming of age story that centers around a character that who doesn’t have their told often. It wasn’t a story trying to preach to its audience. Instead, it was a fun journey of love, friendship, and freedom. I think this one will stay with me for a long time.
